window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>1","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS","question":"In Economics, it is necessary that choice be made mainly because","images":[],"options":{"A":"goods are of various qualities","B":"goods have different prices","C":"resources are inadequate","D":"consumer's wants differ"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In Economics, choices must be made primarily because resources are inadequate. This concept is known as scarcity, which refers to the limited availability of resources to meet unlimited wants. Therefore, the correct option is that resources are inadequate.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>2","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INTRODUCTION TO ECONOMICS : BASIC CONCEPT OF ECONOMICS","question":"If the production of 5 bags of rice are given up by a farmer in order to produce 1 bag of maize, this implies that, to the farmer,","images":[],"options":{"A":"rice has a greater opportunity cost of production than maize","B":"maize has a higher opportunity cost of production than rice","C":"both rice and maize have no opportunity costs of production","D":"rice and maize have equal opportunity costs of production"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The opportunity cost is defined as the value of the next best alternative that is forgone when making a choice. In this case, if the farmer gives up 5 bags of rice to produce 1 bag of maize, it indicates that rice has a greater opportunity cost of production than maize, as the farmer is sacrificing more rice to produce maize.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>3","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"One of the distinguishing features of land is that it is fixed in supply. This means that","images":[],"options":{"A":"its quality is the same everywhere","B":"it can be put to unlimited use","C":"it is free gift of nature","D":"its total surface area cannot be changed"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The statement that land is fixed in supply means that its total surface area cannot be changed. Unlike other factors of production, the quantity of land available is constant, which is a fundamental characteristic of land in economics.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>4","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM","question":"One advantage of a free market economy is that it","images":[],"options":{"A":"guarantees full employment of labour","B":"gives incentives for innovation","C":"guarantees income equally","D":"allocates resources to produce public goods"},"answer":"B","explanation":"One advantage of a free market economy is that it gives incentives for innovation. In a free market, competition encourages businesses to innovate and improve their products and services to attract consumers, leading to economic growth and efficiency.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>5","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC SYSTEM : TYPES AND FEATURES OF ECONOMIC SYSTEM","question":"In a command economy, wages are determined by","images":[],"options":{"A":"the employers","B":"trade unions","C":"central planning committee","D":"forces of demand and supply"},"answer":"C","explanation":"In a command economy, wages are determined by a central planning committee. This is because the government or central authority makes decisions regarding the allocation of resources, including labor, rather than allowing market forces to dictate wages.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>6","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"TOOLS FOR ECONOMIC ANALYSIS: REPRESENTATION OF DATA","question":"Use the diagram below to answer the question      What name is given to the diagram in Figure 1?","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Multiple bar graph","B":"Simple bar chart","C":"Component bar chart","D":"Three-column bar graph"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The diagram above represent a component bar chart. A componet bar chart is used to represent data in which the total magnitude is divided into different or components.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>7","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"A rational consumer of a normal good, ceteris paribus, will do the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"ensuring marginal utility is equal to its price","B":"buying more as income rises","C":"maximizing his satisfaction","D":"buying more at a higher price"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A rational consumer of a normal good will typically buy more as income rises and maximize satisfaction by ensuring that the marginal utility per dollar spent is equal across all goods. However, buying more at a higher price contradicts the law of demand, which states that, ceteris paribus, as the price of a good increases, the quantity demanded decreases.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>8","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"Commodities with negative income elasticities of demand are categorized as","images":[],"options":{"A":"inferior goods","B":"normal goods","C":"substitute goods","D":"complementary goods"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Commodities with negative income elasticities of demand are classified as inferior goods. This means that as consumer income rises, the demand for these goods decreases, as consumers tend to buy higher-quality substitutes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>9","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"The demand for a box of matches by a rich consumer is most likely to be","images":[],"options":{"A":"price elastic","B":"perfectly price elastic","C":"price inelastic","D":"income elastic"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The demand for a box of matches by a rich consumer is most likely to be price inelastic. This is because matches are a low-cost item, and a rich consumer is unlikely to change their quantity demanded significantly in response to price changes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>10","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : ELASTICITY OF DEMAND","question":"Good X has a price elasticity of demand of 0.25. This means it","images":[],"options":{"A":"has many close substitutes","B":"is a luxury good","C":"is not purchased our of habit","D":"has few substitutes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A price elasticity of demand of 0.25 indicates that the good is inelastic, meaning that the quantity demanded changes very little in response to price changes. This typically occurs with goods that have few substitutes, as consumers are less sensitive to price changes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>11","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE THEORY OF DEMAND : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"The demand curve for necessary good without any substitute is usually","images":[],"options":{"A":"vertically sloped","B":"negatively sloped","C":"horizontally sloped","D":"positively sloped"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The demand curve for a necessary good without any substitutes is usually vertically sloped, indicating perfectly inelastic demand. This means that consumers will buy the same quantity regardless of price changes, as they need the good for survival or essential use.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>12","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"A rightward shift of the supply curve of cocoa implies that","images":[],"options":{"A":"the price of cocoa has increased","B":"subsidy on farm equipment has increased","C":"the weather condition has worsened","D":"the number of farmers has reduced"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A rightward shift of the supply curve indicates an increase in supply. This can occur due to factors such as a subsidy on farm equipment, which lowers production costs and encourages more supply. Therefore, the correct option is that a subsidy on farm equipment has increased.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>13","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"Which of the following factors is not a determinant of price elasticity of supply?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Availability of labour","B":"Cost of production","C":"Consumers' income level","D":"Government policy"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Price elasticity of supply is influenced by factors such as availability of labor, cost of production, and government policy. However, consumers' income level is not a determinant of price elasticity of supply; it affects demand elasticity instead. Thus, the correct option is that consumers' income level is not a determinant.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>14","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : MEANING AND DETERMINANTS","question":"An increase in the price of a factor of production in an industry may cause","images":[],"options":{"A":"supply of goods to decrease","B":"more firms to enter the market","C":"the government to increase taxes","D":"the quantity supplied of a factor input to decrease"},"answer":"A","explanation":"An increase in the price of a factor of production typically leads to a decrease in the supply of goods, as higher costs can reduce profitability and discourage production. Therefore, the correct option is that the supply of goods to decrease.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>15","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : DIMINISHING MARGINAL UTILITY AND LAW OF DEMAND","question":"At a point where marginal utility is negative, total utility","images":[],"options":{"A":"is zero","B":"increases","C":"is constant","D":"decreases"},"answer":"D","explanation":"When marginal utility is negative, it means that consuming an additional unit of a good decreases total utility. Therefore, total utility decreases when marginal utility is negative, making the correct option that total utility decreases.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>16","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF CONSUMER BEHAVIOUR : CONSUMER EQUILIBRIUM","question":"If the price of a commodity is higher than its marginal utility, the consumer will","images":[],"options":{"A":"consume more to increase total utility","B":"consume less to increase marginal utility","C":"buy more to minimise total utility","D":"buy more to add to average utility"},"answer":"B","explanation":"If the price of a commodity is higher than its marginal utility, the consumer will consume less to increase marginal utility. This is because consumers aim to maximize their utility, and consuming less of a good that provides less utility than its price will help achieve that. Thus, the correct option is to consume less to increase marginal utility.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>17","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : MARKETING BOARDS","question":"If the price of cassava is fixed above the equilibrium, this policy is meant to","images":[],"options":{"A":"discourage cassava farmers","B":"favour consumers of cassava","C":"encourage cassava farmers","D":"reduce the quantity of cassava supplied"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If the price of cassava is fixed above the equilibrium price, it creates a price floor. This policy is intended to encourage cassava farmers by ensuring they receive a higher price for their product, which can lead to increased production. Therefore, the correct option is 'encourage cassava farmers'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>18","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF SUPPLY : ELASTICITY OF SUPPLY","question":"If the supply of a product with a perfectly elastic demand increases, there will be","images":[],"options":{"A":"an increase in equilibrium price and quantity","B":"a fall in equilibrium price and an increase in equilibrium quantity","C":"a fall in equilibrium quantity while equilibrium price remains constant","D":"an increase in equilibrium quantity while equilibrium price is fixed"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In a perfectly elastic demand scenario, the price remains constant regardless of the quantity supplied. Therefore, if the supply increases, the equilibrium quantity will increase while the equilibrium price remains fixed. Thus, the correct option is 'an increase in equilibrium quantity while equilibrium price is fixed'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>19","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"A firm can increase production in the short-run by","images":[],"options":{"A":"increasing its fixed assets","B":"buying more raw materials","C":"employing skilled managers","D":"building a new factory"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In the short run, a firm can increase production by buying more raw materials, as this allows for the utilization of existing fixed assets to produce more output. Therefore, the correct option is 'buying more raw materials'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>20","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : FACTORS OF PRODUCTION","question":"By installing a larger and more efficient production plant, a firm enjoys","images":[],"options":{"A":"managerial economies","B":"financial economies","C":"technical economies","D":"marketing economies"},"answer":"C","explanation":"By installing a larger and more efficient production plant, a firm benefits from technical economies of scale. This means that as production increases, the cost per unit of output decreases due to more efficient production techniques. Thus, the correct option is 'technical economies'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>21","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : LAWS OF PRODUCTION","question":"When a firm increases the quantities of its variable factor given a fixed factor, the","images":[],"options":{"A":"marginal product of the variable factor will decrease continuously","B":"marginal product of the variable factor rises and later falls","C":"total product will rise continuously","D":"average product will decline and later increase"},"answer":"B","explanation":"When a firm increases the quantities of its variable factor while keeping a fixed factor constant, it typically experiences the law of diminishing returns. Initially, the marginal product of the variable factor may rise, but eventually, it will start to fall as more of the variable factor is added. Therefore, the correct option is 'marginal product of the variable factor rises and later falls'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>22","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT","question":"Use figure 2 to answer the question        The curve labelled Z is","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"average cost curve","B":"marginal cost curve","C":"average variable cost curve","D":"average fixed cost curve"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Curve Z represent the average variabe cost curve. The AVC is the variable cost per unit of output. It is calculated as TVC/Q.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>23","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : PRODUCERS EQUILIBRIUM","question":"Use figure 2 to answer the question      The equilibrium output level is at output","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"Q","B":"R","C":"S","D":"T"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The equilibrium output level is at output Q where curve X which represent the Marginal cost curve cuts the AR which is also the MR from below.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>24","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THE CONCEPT OF COST & REVENUE : CONCEPT","question":"Use figure 2 to answer the question      The interval between curves Y and Z represents","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"options":{"A":"total fixed cost","B":"average fixed cost","C":"average total cost","D":"total cost"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The vertical distance between curves Y and Z represents the difference in values between these two cost curves at each output level.    Curve Y typically represents Average Total cost while curve Z represent Average Variable cost. The difference between ATC and AVC at each level of output is Average Fixed Cost i.e AFC = ATC - AVC","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>25","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"THEORY OF PRODUCTION : LAWS OF PRODUCTION","question":"If a firm's minimum average variable cost exceeds its average revenue, the firm must","images":[],"options":{"A":"employ more labour","B":"increase its production capacity","C":"shut down completely","D":"pay new allowances to its workers"},"answer":"C","explanation":"If a firm's minimum average variable cost exceeds its average revenue, it means that the firm is unable to cover its variable costs. In such a situation, the firm should shut down completely in the short run to minimize losses, as continuing to operate would only increase its losses.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>26","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MARKET STRUCTURE : IMPERFECT MARKET - MONOPOLY","question":"The monopolist's price is always","images":[],"options":{"A":"lower than average revenue","B":"lower than his production cost per unit","C":"higher than average revenue","D":"higher than marginal revenue"},"answer":"C","explanation":"This is because a monopolist can only sell more output by lowering the price, and that price reduction applies to all units sold, not just the additional one. Therefore, the revenue gained from selling one unit (marginal revenue) will be less than the price of that unit (average revenue).","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>27","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"BUSINESS ORGANISATION : LIMITED LIABILITY COMPANIES","question":"A business is a separate legal person if","images":[],"options":{"A":"the business shares its liabilities with the owners","B":"it has all features of a human being","C":"it is governed by a Deed of partnership","D":"it is recognized as a corporate entity"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A business is considered a separate legal person when it is recognized as a corporate entity. This means it can own property, enter contracts, and be liable for debts independently of its owners.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>28","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : STOCK EXCHANGE","question":"Which of the following statements is true of a debenture?","images":[],"options":{"A":"It is a type of share with variable rate of dividend","B":"Its holders are creditors to the company","C":"It is available to all business organizations","D":"Its interest rate increases with profit"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A debenture is a type of debt instrument that is not secured by physical assets or collateral. Its holders are creditors to the company, meaning they have lent money to the company and are entitled to receive interest payments and the return of principal upon maturity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>29","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : DEMAND FOR LABOUR","question":"If an individual refuses a lucrative jon in another town because of ties to his family, this reason can be seen as an impediment to","images":[],"options":{"A":"geographical mobility of labour","B":"occupational mobility of labour","C":"vertical mobility of labour","D":"horizontal mobility of labour"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Refusing a lucrative job in another town due to family ties is an impediment to geographical mobility of labor. Geographical mobility refers to the ability of workers to move to different locations for employment opportunities.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>30","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"LABOUR MARKET AND UNEMPLOYMENT : THE CONCEPT OF UNEMPLOYMENT","question":"If a typist is laid-off because he is not computer literate then he is facing","images":[],"options":{"A":"cyclical unemployment","B":"seasonal unemployment","C":"structural unemployment","D":"frictional unemployment"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The typist is facing structural unemployment because this type of unemployment occurs when there is a mismatch between the skills of the workers and the skills needed for available jobs. In this case, the typist's lack of computer literacy makes him unsuitable for jobs that require such skills.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>31","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"AGRICULTURE IN WEST AFRICA : FEATURES","question":"Capital intensive production method is least adopted in","images":[],"options":{"A":"peasant farming","B":"plantation agriculture","C":"state farming","D":"commercial farming"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Capital intensive production methods are least adopted in peasant farming because this type of farming typically relies on manual labor and traditional methods rather than heavy machinery or technology, which characterizes capital-intensive production.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>32","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC GROWTH AND DEVELOPMENT : INTRODUCTION","question":"Diversification of the economies of developing countries will enable them to","images":[],"options":{"A":"lay emphasis on export of one primary agricultural product","B":"offer more than one product from various sectors for export","C":"export only industrial products","D":"reduce domination of the economies by foreigners"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Diversification of the economies of developing countries will enable them to offer more than one product from various sectors for export. This reduces reliance on a single product and helps stabilize the economy by spreading risk across different sectors.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>33","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INDUSTRY & INDUSTRIALISATION : INTRODUCTION","question":"An industry whose products lose considerable weight after processing must be sited close to the","images":[],"options":{"A":"market","B":"source of raw material","C":"source of power","D":"skilled labour"},"answer":"B","explanation":"An industry whose products lose considerable weight after processing must be sited close to the source of raw material. This is because transporting heavy raw materials to a distant processing facility would be inefficient and costly, so proximity to the raw material source is crucial.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>34","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : PROBLEMS OF NATIONAL INCOME","question":"A factor that may cause the national income to be overstated is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"inclusion of wages of house-keepers","B":"inclusion of the output of subsistence producers","C":"use of value-added method for its calculation","D":"inclusion of pension payments to retirees"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Inclusion of pension payment to retirees overstate national income because pension payments are transfer payments, not payments for current production of goods or services. Including them would inflate national income without corresponding output.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>35","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"NATIONAL INCOME : USES & REASONS FOR MEASURING NATIONAL INCOME","question":"The national income figure is limited as a measure of standard of living because the","images":[],"options":{"A":"prices of commodities remain stable","B":"value of money is constant","C":"real composition of output is not fully known","D":"working conditions are uniform in all countries"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The national income figure is limited as a measure of standard of living because the real composition of output is not fully known. National income accounts aggregate various goods and services, but they do not account for the distribution of income or the quality of goods and services. Therefore, even if the national income is high, it does not necessarily reflect a high standard of living if the output is not diverse or if income is unevenly distributed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>36","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : SUPPLY OF MONEY","question":"Other things being equal, a contraction in the amount of money in circulation will","images":[],"options":{"A":"increase aggregate demand for commodities","B":"lead to fall in the value of money","C":"result in an increase in price level","D":"cause the value of money to rise"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A contraction in the amount of money in circulation will cause the value of money to rise. When there is less money available, each unit of currency becomes more valuable, leading to deflationary pressures. This is because the same amount of goods and services is being chased by fewer dollars, increasing the purchasing power of money.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>37","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INFLATION & DEFLATION : EFFECT","question":"Inflation will usually have a negative effect on","images":[],"options":{"A":"borrowers","B":"balance of payments","C":"shareholders' dividends","D":"sales revenue of firms"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Inflation makes a country's goods and service more expensive relative to foreign goods. they typical leads to decreased exports, increased import. This worsens the current account and therefore negatively affects the BOP","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>38","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : DEMAND FOR MONEY","question":"A factor that positively influences the precautionary motive for holding money is","images":[],"options":{"A":"high rate of interest","B":"convenient system of payment","C":"short interval between paydays","D":"high degree of uncertainty"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A factor that positively influences the precautionary motive for holding money is a high degree of uncertainty. When individuals or businesses face uncertainty about future income or expenses, they are more likely to hold onto cash as a safeguard against unforeseen circumstances, rather than investing or spending it.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>39","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MONEY : TYPES OF MONEY","question":"Which of the following is not a form of money?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Bank notes","B":"Current account deposits","C":"Promissory notes","D":"Fiat coins"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Promissory notes are not considered a form of money in the traditional sense. While they can represent a promise to pay a certain amount, they are not universally accepted as a medium of exchange like bank notes, current account deposits, or fiat coins. Money must be widely accepted and easily transferable, which promissory notes are not.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>40","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"FINANCIAL INSTITUTION : COMMERCIAL BANKS","question":"Which of the following items is not an asset to commercial banks?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Shareholders' funds","B":"Physical buildings and equipment","C":"Loans granted to customers","D":"Vehicle and office equipment"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Shareholders' funds are not considered an asset to commercial banks; rather, they represent the equity or net worth of the bank. Assets are resources owned by the bank that can generate future economic benefits, such as loans and physical equipment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>41","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : BUDGET","question":"In a deficit budget, the expected revenue would be","images":[],"options":{"A":"higher than proposed expenditure","B":"lower than proposed expenditure","C":"equal to proposed expenditure","D":"falling as consumers' incomes increases"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In a deficit budget, the expected revenue is lower than proposed expenditure. This means that the government anticipates spending more than it will earn, leading to a budget deficit.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>42","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"A flat tax rate of 10% levied per unit of a commodity is an example of","images":[],"options":{"A":"specific tax","B":"progressive tax","C":"regressive tax","D":"ad valorem tax"},"answer":"A","explanation":"A flat tax rate of 10% levied per unit of a commodity is an example of a specific tax. Specific taxes are fixed amounts charged per unit of a good or service, regardless of its price.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>43","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : TAX","question":"Tax avoidance best refers to attempts by a tax payer to","images":[],"options":{"A":"conceal income deliberately thereby paying no tax","B":"always seek for tax holidays during which he will not pay tax","C":"legally exploit the loopholes in tax laws to pay less tax","D":"escape illegally from the tax net thereby paying no tax at all"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Tax avoidance refers to the legal strategies that taxpayers use to minimize their tax liabilities, often by exploiting loopholes in tax laws. This is different from tax evasion, which is illegal.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>44","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : TAX","question":"If governments in developing countries want to raise revenue, then the major source to rely on is","images":[],"options":{"A":"royalties and rent","B":"grants and loans","C":"sale of government assets","D":"indirect taxes"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In developing countries, indirect taxes are often a major source of revenue for governments. These taxes are levied on goods and services rather than on income, making them a significant source of funding.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>45","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : BALANCE OF TRADE & PAYMENT","question":"In which section of a country's balance of payments account will the inflow of long-term investments be recorded?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Balance of trade section","B":"Current account section","C":"Capital account section","D":"Official financing section"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The inflow of long-term investments is recorded in the Capital account section of a country's balance of payments. The Capital account includes transactions that involve the purchase and sale of assets, such as investments in businesses or real estate, which are considered long-term investments.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>46","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"PUBLIC FINANCE : CLASSIFICATION OF TAX","question":"The table below shows the percentage paid as tax on different income levels. Use it to answer the question    Tax System $100$500$1000Q 10% 10% 10%T 90% 70% 30%S 20% 65% 40%R 10% 40% 70%    Which tax system is progressive? Tax system","images":[],"options":{"A":"Q","B":"T","C":"S","D":"R"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A progressive tax system is one where the tax rate increases as the income level increases. In the table provided, Tax system S shows increasing tax rates as income rises (20% on $100, 65% on $500, and 40% on $1000), indicating that it is a progressive tax system.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>47","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"INTERNATIONAL TRADE : INTRODUCTION","question":"Dumping of goods is not desirable since it leads to","images":[],"options":{"A":"an increase in the wage bill of the importing country","B":"unemployment in the importing country","C":"production of more local goods","D":"an increase in tax revenue from local industries"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Dumping of goods, which refers to selling products in a foreign market at a price lower than their normal value, can lead to unemployment in the importing country. This occurs because local industries may struggle to compete with the lower-priced imported goods, potentially leading to job losses.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>48","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC INTEGRATION : OBJECTIVES, LEVELS OF AND FEATURES","question":"A long-term adverse balance of payments can be corrected by","images":[],"options":{"A":"reducing or removing export duties","B":"revaluing the domestic currency","C":"using up foreign currency reserves","D":"receiving gifts from other countries"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A long-term adverse balance of payments can be corrected by revaluing the domestic currency. Revaluation makes exports more expensive and imports cheaper, which can help to balance the payments by reducing the trade deficit.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>49","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"ECONOMIC INTEGRATION : PROBLEMS OF ECONOMIC INTEGRATION IN WEST AFRICA- ECOWAS","question":"Which of the following benefits is not applicable to economic integration?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Availability of variety of commodities","B":"Free mobility of factors of production","C":"Expansion of market size","D":"Complete independence of each nation"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Complete independence of each nation is not a benefit of economic integration. Economic integration typically involves countries working together to reduce trade barriers and increase cooperation, which inherently requires some level of interdependence among the nations involved.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Economics>2025>50","subject":"Economics","year":"2025","type":"Objective","topic":"MAJOR NATURAL RESOURCES : OPEC","question":"The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) prevents excess global supply of crude oil by","images":[],"options":{"A":"buying up the extra volume produced by members of the oil market","B":"fixing production quotas for all member countries","C":"expelling erring members countries from the organization","D":"taking legal actions against members at the world court"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) aims to manage the supply of oil in the global market to stabilize prices. One of the primary methods OPEC uses to achieve this is by fixing production quotas for its member countries. By setting limits on how much oil each member can produce, OPEC can prevent excess supply that could lead to lower prices. This approach helps maintain a balance between supply and demand in the oil market.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];